1. CNN AND TRANSFORMER FOUNDATIONS
Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) remain the workhorse for
spatial image processing tasks: denoising, demosaicing, super-
resolution, and local tone mapping.

Convolution Layer:
  Output[y, x, k] = sum_c sum_i sum_j Input[y+i, x+j, c] * Kernel[i, j, c, k] + Bias[k]

Activation Functions:
  ReLU: f(x) = max(0, x)
  Leaky ReLU: f(x) = x if x > 0 else alpha * x, alpha = 0.01
  GELU: f(x) = x * Phi(x), where Phi is the Gaussian CDF.
  SiLU/Swish: f(x) = x * sigmoid(x)

Residual Block (ResNet): Output = Input + F(Input), where F is a
small sub-network (typically two conv layers). Enables training of
very deep networks (100+ layers) without vanishing gradients.

Transformer Attention for image restoration (e.g., DLSS Ray
Reconstruction, image inpainting):
  Scaled Dot-Product Attention:
    Attention(Q, K, V) = softmax(Q K^T / sqrt(d_k)) V

  Multi-Head Self-Attention (MHSA):
    MultiHead(Q, K, V) = Concat(head_1, ..., head_h) W^O
    where head_i = Attention(Q W_i^Q, K W_i^K, V W_i^V)

  Vision Transformer (ViT): image is split into patches, each patch
  is linearly embedded into a token, and a standard Transformer
  encoder processes the set of tokens. Positional encoding preserves
  spatial structure.

2. DIFFUSION MODELS AND GENERATIVE IMAGING
Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models (DDPM) are the dominant
generative paradigm for high-quality image synthesis.

Forward Process (gradually add Gaussian noise):
  q(x_t | x_{t-1}) = N(x_t; sqrt(1 - beta_t) * x_{t-1}, beta_t * I)
  q(x_t | x_0) = N(x_t; sqrt(alpha_bar_t) * x_0, (1 - alpha_bar_t) * I)
  where alpha_t = 1 - beta_t, alpha_bar_t = prod_{s=1}^{t} alpha_s.

Reverse Process (learn to denoise):
  p_theta(x_{t-1} | x_t) = N(x_{t-1}; mu_theta(x_t, t), sigma_t^2 * I)
  The network epsilon_theta(x_t, t) predicts the added noise.

Simplified training loss (Ho et al. 2020):
  L = E_{t, x_0, epsilon} [ || epsilon - epsilon_theta(x_t, t) ||^2 ]

Applications in GIOP:
  - Super-resolution: condition on low-res image.
  - HDR reconstruction: generate clipped highlights from SDR input.
  - Text-to-image: condition on CLIP text embeddings for creative
    previsualization and concept art.

3. GENERATIVE ADVERSARIAL NETWORKS (GANs)
GANs remain relevant for fast, single-pass image enhancement.

Architecture: Generator G and Discriminator D play a minimax game:
  min_G max_D E_{x~p_data}[log D(x)] + E_{z~p_z}[log(1 - D(G(z)))]

Perceptual loss for image-to-image translation: combine L1/L2
pixel loss with VGG feature-space loss:
  L_perceptual = L_pixel + lambda * sum ||VGG_i(G(x)) - VGG_i(y)||^2

GIOP-approved use cases:
  - Fast RAW-to-RGB conversion for previews.
  - Style transfer for dailies look development.
  - Texture synthesis for VFX patch repair.

4. AI-NATIVE ISP PIPELINE
Traditional ISPs use a fixed sequence of hand-tuned algorithms.
AI-native ISPs replace most or all of these stages with a single
trained neural network.

Input: RAW Bayer data (linear, unprocessed).
Output: final viewable RGB or scene-referred linear ACEScg.

Architecture typically consists of:
  - A U-Net backbone with multi-scale feature extraction.
  - A Transformer or ResNet bottleneck for global context.
  - Dedicated heads for demosaicing, white balance, noise reduction,
    and local tone mapping, trained jointly.

GIOP mandates that any AI-ISP must also output:
  - A linearized, scene-referred intermediate (the "digital negative")
    before the tone curve is applied.
  - A confidence map indicating regions where the AI's reconstruction
    may be unreliable (e.g., specular highlights, fine text).

Leading implementations (2026): Visionary.ai, Chips&Media AI-ISP,
Qualcomm Spectra Cognitive ISP.

5. AI COLOR GRADING AND APPEARANCE
AI agents are now capable of performing complete color grades.

Agentic grading workflow (LumiVideo, AceTone 2026):
  Perception: analyze shot content, recognize faces, skin, sky.
  Reasoning: compare against a reference look library or textual
    description ("golden hour, warm, soft contrast").
  Execution: apply primary corrections (exposure, contrast,
    saturation, white balance) followed by secondary masks and
    qualifiers.
  Reflection: compare result to reference, iterate.

Text-to-LUT generation: a diffusion or transformer model generates
a 3D LUT (e.g., 33^3 cube) from a descriptive text prompt. GIOP
validates generated LUTs for:
  - Smoothness (no discontinuities).
  - Gamut legality (no values exceed BT.2020 or chosen target).
  - Skin tone preservation (error < CIEDE2000 threshold on a
    standard skin tone panel).

6. GENERATIVE VIDEO AND FILM PRODUCTION
Models such as Alibaba Wan2.7-Video, Meta Movie Gen, and OpenAI
Sora represent the frontier of generative video.

Capabilities:
  - Text-to-video with temporal coherence.
  - Video inpainting and object removal.
  - Frame interpolation and super-resolution.
  - Virtual cinematography (camera path synthesis).

GIOP defines a metadata standard for generative video:
  - The prompt and model version are embedded as ACESclip metadata.
  - A hash of the starting noise seed and all conditioning inputs
    is recorded for reproducibility.
  - Generative content is flagged with a C2PA manifest.

7. AI STANDARDS AND CERTIFICATION
Several international standards govern AI in imaging.

JPEG AI (ISO/IEC 6048-1): a learning-based image compression
standard achieving up to 60% bitrate reduction over JPEG 2000
at equivalent quality. GIOP provides the reference IDT-to-display
pipeline for JPEG AI evaluation.

SMPTE AI Engineering Document: best practices for AI in broadcast
and cinema, including model card templates, dataset documentation,
and performance reporting.

C2PA (Coalition for Content Provenance and Authenticity):
cryptographically binds metadata (creator, date, camera, edits,
AI operations) to the image or video asset. GIOP mandates C2PA
compliance for any AI-augmented deliverable.

8. AI ETHICS AND AUTHENTICITY
AI in imaging carries ethical responsibilities.

Deepfake detection: forensic analysis of spatial and temporal
artifacts. GIOP endorses detectors based on frequency-domain
analysis and physiological signal consistency (heart rate from
facial micro-color changes).

Bias mitigation: AI models trained on imbalanced datasets can
distort skin tones, facial features, or textures for under-
represented groups. GIOP requires:
  - Training data with demonstrated diversity of skin tones
    (Fitzpatrick scale coverage), age, and gender.
  - Validation on standardized fairness benchmarks.
  - Reporting of per-group accuracy metrics.

Content authenticity: GIOP-certified cameras embed a hardware root
of trust at capture time. Any AI operation subsequent to capture
must be recorded in the C2PA manifest, creating an auditable chain
from photon to pixel.

9. AI TRAINING DATA AND BIAS MITIGATION
The quality and fairness of an AI model are bounded by its
training data.

Dataset requirements for GIOP certification:
  - Minimum 100,000 images or 10,000 video clips.
  - Coverage of all 12 Fitzpatrick skin types.
  - Scene types: indoor, outdoor, studio, night, mixed.
  - Illuminants: D65, A, fluorescent, LED, mixed.
  - Demographics: balanced age, gender, ethnicity.

Bias auditing: a held-out test set with equal representation of
each subgroup is used to measure per-group PSNR, SSIM, and
CIEDE2000. Any group showing an error more than 20% above the
global average triggers mandatory model retraining.

10. AI MODEL VALIDATION AND AUDITING
Before an AI model is allowed in a GIOP-certified pipeline, it
must pass a battery of tests.

Synthetic test signals: known inputs (e.g., linear ramps, color
charts, resolution wedges) are passed through the model. Outputs
are verified for:
  - Linearity preservation (no unintended tone curve).
  - Color accuracy (CIEDE2000 < 2.0 on ColorChecker).
  - Resolution (MTF > 50% at Nyquist).

Stress tests: extreme exposures, high ISO noise, specular
highlights, fine repetitive patterns (moire risk), and low-light
scenes are evaluated for artifacts.

Continual monitoring: in production, a subset of frames is
periodically extracted and tested against the original validation
metrics to detect model drift or data poisoning.

